One thing to note here: in swagger you have both types ("string") and formats ("uuid"). If you are using this particular format, it's not present in the Bravado client by default. Here's some code that adds it:

```
from uuid import UUID

def validate_uuid(s):
    try:
        UUID(s)
    except ValueError:
        raise SwaggerValidationError("Invalid UUID: {}".format(s))


uuid_format = SwaggerFormat(
    format="uuid",
    to_wire=lambda uuid: str(uuid),
    to_python=lambda s: s,
    validate=validate_uuid,
    description="UUID format",
)

config = {
    "formats": [uuid_format]
}

client = SwaggerClient.from_url(some_url, config=config)
```

On a second thought, are you sure this code would work? E.g. given aMaxAge = 0x00123456:
on LE machines: aMaxAge => 0x56341200, buf = { 00, 12, 34, 56 } - good order, length too long
on BE machines: aMaxAge => 0x00123456, buf = { 56, 34, 12 } - reversed order, good length.
Or am I missing something?
I think this should give the correct result:
```C++
aMaxAge = Encoding::BigEndian::HostSwap32(aMaxAge);
coapOption.mLength = 4;
coapOption.mValue = static_cast<uint8_t *>(&aMaxAge);
// skip preceding zeros, but make sure mLength is at least 1
while (coapOption.mValue[0] == 0 && coapOption.mLength > 1) {
    coapOption.mValue++;
    coapOption.mLength--;
}
```
, but not so sure if short and vague is better than long and clear.
